Title : John Cade (antiquarian)
Text : '''John Cade''' (1734–1806) was an English tradesman and antiquary. Retiring from business, he took up the study of Roman remains around [[County Durham]], putting forward hypotheses of reconstruction of [[Roman road]]s, in particular, that were controversial.

==Life==
Cade was born in January 1734, at [[Darlington]], where he was educated at [[Darlington]] grammar school. Entering a wholesale linendraper's firm in London, he was promoted as head of the counting-house, and subsequently became a partner in a branch of the concern at [[Dublin]].<ref name="DNB">{{cite DNB|wstitle=Cade, John (1734-1806)|volume=8}}</ref>

Cade retired from business, with an independent financial position. He died at [[Gainford, County Durham|Gainford]] 10 December 1806, and was buried at Darlington.<ref name="DNB"/>

==Works==
Cade corresponded with [[Thomas Reynolds (minister)|Thomas Reynolds]], [[Sir Richard Kaye, 6th Baronet|Richard Kaye]] and [[Richard Gough (antiquarian)|Richard Gough]]; but was strongly controverted by [[William Hutchinson (topographer)|William Hutchinson]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Thomas Reynolds|title=Iter britanniarum; or, that part of the Itinerary of Antoninus which relates to Britain, with a new comment|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ELksAAAAMAAJ&pg=PR23|year=1799|publisher=Printed by J. Burges|page=xxiii}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=John Nichols|author2=Samuel Bentley|title=Literary Anecdotes of the Eighteenth Century: Comprizing Biographical Memoirs of William Bowyer, Printer, F.S.A., and Many of His Learned Friends; an Incidental View of the Progress and Advancement of Literature in this Kingdom During the Last Century; and Biographical Anecdotes of a Considerable Number of Eminent Writers and Ingenious Artists; with a Very Copious Index|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xB1AAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA316|year=1814|publisher=Printed for the author, by Nichols, son, and Bentley|pages=316–7}}</ref> Not a member of the [[Society of Antiquaries of London]], he contributed papers to ''[[Archaeologia (London)|Archæologia]]'', their journal. These included:<ref name="DNB"/>

* ''Conjectures concerning some undescribed Roman Roads and other Antiquities in the County of Durham'', vii. 74, an attempt to trace [[Icknield Street]] in County Durham;<ref>{{cite book|title=The critical review, or annals of literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I41KAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA179|year=1785|pages=179–80}}</ref>
* ''A Letter from Rev. Dr. Sharp, Archdeacon of Northumberland, to Mr. Cade'', vii. 82; 
* ''Conjectures on the name of the Roman Station Vinovium or Binchester'', ix. 276;<ref>{{cite book|title=Archaeologia: Or Miscellaneous Tracts Relating to Antiquity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ordJAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA160|year=1785|publisher=The Society|page=160}}</ref> and 
* ''Some Observations on the Roman Station of Cataractonium, with an account of the Antiquities in the neighbourhood of Piersbridge and Gainford; in a letter to Richard Gough, Esq.'', x. 54.

Cade collected illustrations for a copy of [[Edmund Gibson]]'s edition of [[William Camden]]'s ''Britannia'', and supplied Gough with many corrections for his edition. He sent [[John Nichols (printer)|John Nichols]] ''Some Conjectures on the Formation of Peat-mosses in the mountainous parts of the Counties of Durham, Northumberland'', printed in the ''[[Gentleman's Magazine]]'', lix. 967.<ref name="DNB"/>

